# Delete

Discard an abandoned, accidental, or partially-deleted governed change without
relying on private knowledge of `artifacts/changes/<slug>` or `.git/slipway`
internals. `delete` removes local governed state; it is distinct from `cancel`,
which archives a terminal record.

## Invocation
```bash
slipway delete --change <slug>            # dry-run plan (deletes nothing)
slipway delete --change <slug> --yes      # discard bundle + runtime binding
slipway delete --change <slug> --worktree --yes   # also remove the worktree
slipway delete --change <slug> --archived --yes   # purge an archived record
```

## Contract
- Default (no `--yes`) prints a dry-run plan of exactly what would be removed and
  deletes nothing. Pass `--yes` to execute.
- Removes the governed bundle (`artifacts/changes/<slug>`) and the per-change
  runtime binding. `--worktree` also removes the bound git worktree; `--archived`
  purges an archived terminal record under `artifacts/changes/archived/<slug>`.
- Fails closed: refuses to remove a worktree with uncommitted tracked changes
  unless `--force`; never deletes the implementation or pushed PR branch.
- A refusal blocks the whole operation so nothing is partially deleted.
- Reports which targets were deleted, skipped, or refused.
- Use this when `status`/`next`/recovery report a change that is abandoned,
  broken, or bound to another worktree (they route here with the exact `--change`
  command).

## Flags
- `--change <slug>`: target a specific change (required when not resolvable as the active change)
- `--worktree`: also remove the bound git worktree
- `--archived`: purge an archived terminal record instead of active state
- `--yes`: execute the deletion (otherwise a dry-run plan is printed)
- `--force`: override the uncommitted-tracked-changes refusal on worktree removal
- `--json`: JSON output
